04328nam a22005295i 9780520933392DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20072007cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209333927 a10.1525/97805209333922doi  a(DE-B1597)520755  a(OCoLC)173816785  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aMUS0060002bisacsh1 aFosler-Lussier, Danielle, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMusic Divided :bBartók's Legacy in Cold War Culture /cDanielle Fosler-Lussier. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2007] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (252 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCalifornia Studies in 20th-Century Music ;v700tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface -- tNote on Hungarian Pronunciation -- t1 Bartók's Concerto for Orchestra and the Demise of Hungary's "Third Road" -- t2 A Compromised Composer -- t3 "Bartók Is Ours" -- t4 Bartók and His Publics -- t5 Beyond the Folk Song -- t6 The "Bartók Question" and the Politics of Dissent -- tEpilogue East -- tEpilogue West -- tAppendix 1: Compositions by Bartók Broadcast on Hungarian Radio -- tAppendix 2: Biographical Notes -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMusic Divided explores how political pressures affected musical life on both sides of the iron curtain during the early years of the cold war. In this groundbreaking study, Danielle Fosler-Lussier illuminates the pervasive political anxieties of the day through particular attention to artistic, music-theoretical, and propagandistic responses to the music of Hungary's most renowned twentieth-century composer, Béla Bartók. She shows how a tense period of political transition plagued Bartók's music and imperiled those who took a stand on its aesthetic value in the emerging socialist state. Her fascinating investigation of Bartók's reception outside of Hungary demonstrates that Western composers, too, formulated their ideas about musical style under the influence of ever-escalating cold war tensions.Music Divided surveys Bartók's role in provoking negative reactions to "accessible" music from Pierre Boulez, Hermann Scherchen, and Theodor Adorno. It considers Bartók's influence on the youthful compositions and thinking of Bruno Maderna and Karlheinz Stockhausen, and it outlines Bartók's legacy in the music of the Hungarian composers András Mihály, Ferenc Szabó, and Endre Szervánszky. These details reveal the impact of local and international politics on the selection of music for concert and radio programs, on composers' choices about musical style, on government radio propaganda about music, on the development of socialist realism, and on the use of modernism as an instrument of political action.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aMusicxHistory and criticismx20th century. 0aMusicxPolitical aspectsxHistoryx20th centuryxHungary. 0aMusicxPolitical aspectsxHistoryx20th century. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Classical.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520933392423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520933392.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles